Demo FSD (Supervised)

The Future of Transport

Tesla uses billions of miles of anonymous real-world driving data to train Full Self-Driving (Supervised) to take care of the most stressful parts of daily driving while helping make the roads safer for you and others. When enabled, your vehicle will drive you almost anywhere with your active supervision, requiring minimal intervention.

View Safety Report

Full Self-Driving (Supervised) is currently available in the U.S., Canada, China, Mexico, Puerto Rico, Australia, New Zealand and South Korea and will come to other regions in future updates.1

# Safety

#### Engineered to Protect Everyone

# 5

## -Star

#### Ratings

#### Data-Driven Safety

#### Safer Over Time

# Safety Is Paramount

#### Safety is at the center of every product we build. This is why safety features are included in every vehicle we produce—all with the goal of making our roads as safe as possible for everyone on them. Learn More

# The Safest Crash Is No Crash

#### All Tesla vehicles are equipped with safety features that can help anticipate or avoid accidents. Our technology is only getting better, making Tesla vehicles the safest in the world. Learn More

# Developed in the Real World [...] #### Tesla vehicle structures are designed to cushion and protect the battery in the event of an accident. Onboard systems will automatically disconnect the high-voltage battery upon impact. If a battery fire does occur, the battery pack is designed to spread heat away from the cabin to protect occupants.

#### Dashcam clips include details like date, time, driving speed and Self-Driving status. Impact data from crashes is sent to Tesla and used by our safety engineering team to improve and develop new and existing safety features.2 These learnings and developments are then shared with every Tesla vehicle in our global fleet through over-the-air software updates—so your Tesla gets better and safer over time.

View Safety Report [...] # Prepared for Impact

#### The chassis and frame of the vehicle are designed to absorb the energy of a crash before it gets to the cabin. This helps protect occupants and the battery from direct impact energy, reducing the likelihood of injury. This design also helps reduce impact severity for the other vehicle, keeping its occupants safer.

# Reactive Airbags

#### Advanced airbags are tuned to deploy according to crash type and different-sized occupants. This includes active venting that changes the amount of pressure within the inflated cushion by releasing gas according to the expected crash severity. Additional far-side airbags between first-row occupants help prevent occupant-to-occupant contact during side impacts.
